abortion wa made for horror in abortion a mother is pitted against her child the madonna becomes medea and the child usually a symbol of innocence is experienced a an invading enemy the distortion of the pregnant woman body are mirrored in the dismemberment of the fetus and the helplessness and terror felt by many woman facing unwanted pregnancy are mirrored in the unfeeling unthinking total powerlessness of the embryo the present is turned against the future the doctor work to end a life and the womb becomes a battleground regardless of your political or moral belief there enough material there to give anyone nightmare perhaps this is why abortion and unwanted or monstrous pregnancy have been explored countless time in horror movie comic and prose and horror ha treated these topic much le reductively than one might expect approaching them primarily in emotional or visceral term and secondarily in moral term rather than primarily in political term there are at least three obvious approach creator could take to abortionhorror the two ive run across most frequently are grotesquerie and grief horror focusing on a monstrous baby and horror focusing on a haunted postabortive parent i wont attempt a complete survey of abortionrelated imagery in horror these are merely observation about how horror ha managed to address our intense and conflicting fear around unwanted pregnancy and the unborn in the monster show a cultural history of horror david j skal argues that the 1960s and 1970s brought a wave of monstrousbaby movie which he link to the terrible birth defect caused by thalidomide and the growing movement for legalized abortion rosemary baby of course and the bodyhorror flick eraserhead david lynch and the brood david cronenberg plus a score of much lesser flick like humanoid from the deep and it alive and it sequel he focus on the hit movie alien the poster art for alien wa deceptively simple and evocative a cracked egg in a dark void and the tag line in space no one can hear you scream whether the space wa internal or external wa not made clear these image reflect and perhaps strengthen the real revulsion many woman experience at the thought of an unwanted pregnancy it impossible to spend five minute reading an online discussion of abortion without coming across a description of the unborn child a a parasite or a tumor a mass of cell an intruder invader alienalmost a rapist a anyone who watched rosemary baby can see the image of monstrous child recur in horror not because the filmmaker want to get u to donate to planned parenthood but because they tap into preexisting fear in the audience but there is another large subgenre of abortion horror for reason not entirely clear to me ive run across this other kind of horror almost exclusively in short story and independent comic these are story about ghost the return of the child who wa never allowed to be born a with the monsterchild film not all of these work are very good f paul wilson 1989 novella bucket for example is an uninspired rendition of an obvious central ideathe child an abortionist killed returning to wreak their revenge tanith lee short story the abortionist horse a nightmare reprinted in 2001s year best fantasy and horror feature her characteristic overripe prose redeemed by eerie imagery lee describes a pregnant woman alone in a country house who cant stop hearing the clipclop of a ghostly horse which once carried a rural woman who performed illegal abortion the inescapable hoof beat a horrific echo of the heartbeat in her womb both reflect and heighten her own fear about her pregnancy leading up to a bloody tragic ending for genuinely artistic representation of abortionashorror however the best example are comic alan moore watchman v for vendetta suffuses his returnofrepressedconscience horror comic a small killing with imagery of abortion symbolically portrayed a the destruction of youthful innocence this symbolism seems to have escaped most readersdespite it ubiquity in the comicperhaps because of the comic equallyblatant leftwing political slant once again the force of the abortion imagery is best understood by reading emotionally and morally not politically a similar collision of the politics of abortion and the emotional aftermath of the act occurs in jaime hernandezs fly on the ceiling the true story of isabel in mexico one of the darkest installment in the extraordinary comic series love and rocket fly may depict a woman psychological breakdown or her encounter with the devil or both her abortion is depicted by showing a scene of generic creepy protester outside a clinic the politics of this depiction might even be called antiprolife and yet the story of isabels grief and partial healing follows a more complex emotional and symbolic logic her healing begin when she becomes the housekeeper for a lonely single father becoming part of their family although her maternal idyll doesnt last it effectively show that both her abortion and her divorce are experience from which shes still recovering the comic doesnt take a final stand on whether the satanic figure who stalk isabel are projection of her own catholic guilt and shame or if by her action she ha opened herself to visionary and terrifying experience of the supernatural i had expected to find one other subgenre of horror the horror of repression in which the focus is not on the monstrous baby or the haunted adult but on the social pressure controlling woman choice and circumstance john carpenter did a master of horror installment called prolife in which a woman carrying a demonic fetus is prevented from aborting by her prolife relative i leave it to the viewer to determine whether this explicitly politicized treatment of abortionhorror succeeds a art an understandably obscure french movie house of voice at first seems like it will be repressionhorror since it center on a woman hiding her unwanted pregnancy in a 1950s orphanage and is suffused with image of binding covering and cleansing however by it confusing hallucinatory end it embedded firmly in the second haunting subgenre even david skal who often overpoliticizes his reading of horror movie acknowledges the demonization of fetal image doe not lend itself to a simplistic ideological interpretationmonster child are not exactly prolife or prochoice but like the sick joke articulate unspoken aspect on both side abortion horror whatever it creator political sympathy explores the fear and grief and blood so often ignored or repressed by both side of the political battle
